        option: [`Imbalance in α-globin and β-globin chain production`, `Increased susceptibility to oxidative stress`,`Reduced synthesis of hemoglobin F`,` Relative deficiency of vitamin B`,`Impaired utilization of iron by erythroblasts`],
        optionFeedback: [` The findings are consistent with a severe form of thalassemia, which is prevalent in Mediterranean countries. In this part of the world, β-thalassemia predominates and is usually caused by point mutations that interfere with the production of beta-globin chains. In the absence of β-globin chains, unpaired α-globin chains precipitate in red cell precursors and cause apoptosis. Chronic tissue hypoxia stunts growth, and severe chronic anemia and resultant high levels of erythropoietin drive the expansion of immature red cell progenitors, which distort bones and “spread” to extramedullary sites, such as the liver and spleen, which are enlarged due to extramedullary hematopoiesis. Note that while the relative reticulocyte count is high, the absolute reticulocyte count is low for the severity of the anemia. `,`Increased susceptibility to oxidative stress occurs in glucose-6-phosphatase-dehydrogenase deficiency because, in the absence of this enzyme, there is impaired production of reduced glutathione, which protects against oxidant stress triggered by ingestion of certain drugs or by infections. `,`Hemoglobin F levels in β-thalassemia tend to be normal or even increased, possibly because cells with residual fetal hemoglobin have a survival advantage`,`Relative deficiency of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> does not contribute to the severity of anemia in β-thalassemia, whereas relative deficiency of folate (which is marginally present in many diets) may worsen the anemia.`,`Impaired utilization of iron by erythroblasts is a feature of the anemia of chronic inflammation, not thalassemia. `],
