        q: `A 14-year-old girl has had a history of fatigue and weakness for her entire life. She has not undergone puberty. She has hepatosplenomegaly. CBC shows hemoglobin of 9.1 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL), hematocrit of 26.7% (36%–50%), MCV of 66 &#181;m<sup>3</sup> (78–98 &#181;m<sup>3</sup>), platelet count of 150,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>), and WBC count of 3,670/mm<sup>3</sup> (3,200–9,800/mm<sup>3</sup>). Special stains reveal aggregates of alpha globin in normoblasts. Which of the following derangements is the most likely cause of anemia in this patient?`,
