        optionFeedback: [`Sequestration of iron in bone marrow macrophages is a feature of the anemia of chronic inflammation. It is caused by increased level of hepcidin.`,` The findings are consistent with β-thalassemia, in which defects in β-globin production lead to unpaired α-globin chains, which form aggregates in red cell progenitors. These aggregates generate oxidative stress and also induce the unfolded protein response, both of which may contribute to death by the mitochondrial (intrinsic) pathway of apoptosis. `,`Reduced absorption of dietary iron is also a feature of the anemia of chronic inflammation, whereas iron uptake is increased in thalassemia due to suppression of hepcidin production in the liver.`,`Erythropoietin production is increased in thalassemia due to renal hypoxia.`,`Sensitivity of red cells to complement-mediated lysis is a feature of paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria, a rare, acquired condition in which red cells are produced without certain surface proteins that protect cells from complement.`],
