        q: `A 12-year-old boy has a history of episodes of severe abdominal, chest, and back pain since early childhood. On physical examination, he is afebrile, and there is no organomegaly. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin of 10.2 g/dL (11.4–15.5), platelet count of 194,000/mm<sup>3 </sup>(150,000–400,000/ mm<sup>3</sup>), and WBC count of 9,020/mm<sup>3 </sup>(3,800–12,700/mm<sup>3</sup>). The peripheral blood smear shows sickled red cells and occasional nucleated RBCs. Hemoglobin electrophoresis shows 1% hemoglobin A<sub>2</sub>, and 93% hemoglobin S. Hydroxyurea therapy is found to be beneficial in this patient. An increase in which of the following is the most likely basis for its therapeutic efficacy?`,
