        q: `A 25-year-old woman has a 3-year history of arthralgias. Physical examination shows no joint deformity, but she appears slightly pale. Laboratory studies show total RBC count of 4.7 million/mm<sup>3 </sup>(3.5–5.5 million/mm<sup>3</sup>), hemoglobin of 12.5 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL), hematocrit of 37.1% (36%–46%), platelet count of 217,000/mm<sup>3 </sup>(150,000–400,000/ mm<sup>3</sup>), and WBC count of 5890/mm<sup>3 </sup>(4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). The peripheral blood smear shows hypochromic and microcytic RBCs. Total serum iron and ferritin levels are normal. Hemoglobin electrophoresis shows 93% hemoglobin A<sub>1</sub> with elevated hemoglobin A<sub>2</sub> level of 5.8% and hemoglobin F level of 1.2%. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?`,
