        optionFeedback: [`Anemia of chronic disease is not associated with elevated HbA2; red cells may be on the small end of normal but are usually not microcytic and hypochromic.`,`Autoimmune hemolytic anemia causes increased erythropoiesis but there is no change in the production of beta-globin chains.`,` The only common cause of increased HbA2 is β-thalassemia. HbA2 is a minor hemoglobin that consists of two alpha chains and two delta chains; the latter are encoded by the delta globin locus, which is located near the beta-globin locus on chromosome 11. When the expression of beta chains is decreased, as in β-thalassemia minor (also known as β-thalassemia trait), the delta chains compete more effectively for pairing with alpha chains, increasing the concentration of HbA2. `,`Infection with Plasmodium vivax also would be associated with red cell hemolysis and normal or increased red cell size (due to reticulocytosis); organisms might also be seen within red cells.`,`E. Although iron deficiency anemia is also associated with hypochromic and microcytic red cells, normal serum iron and ferritin levels exclude iron deficiency.`],
