        option: [` Hemolysis of antibody-coated cells`, ` Hematopoietic stem cell defect`,` Impaired globin synthesis`,`Mechanical fragmentation of RBCs`,`Oxidative injury to hemoglobin`],
        optionFeedback: [` Hydrops is consistent with heart failure due to severe anemia and jaundice, and the positive direct Coombs test is consistent with antibody-mediated RBC hemolysis. Historically, the most likely cause of hemolytic disease of the newborn was Rh incompatibility, in which a multiparous Rh-negative mother is immunized by previous pregnancies against Rh D antigen. Fortunately, this complication of pregnancy is now rare thanks to routine administration of an antibody preparation against Rh D to Rh-negative mothers around the time of birth. These antibodies clear Rh-positive fetal red cells and prevent immunization of the mother. `,`A hematopoietic stem cell defect could produce severe anemia and hydrops but would not be associated with a positive direct Coombs test.`,`Impaired globin synthesis as in the thalassemias could produce severe anemia and hydrops but would not be associated with a positive direct Coombs test.`,`Mechanical fragmentation of RBCs occurs in microangiopathic hemolytic anemias and is caused by traumatic injury to red cells. It is not consistent with this clinical scenario and would be Coombs test negative `,`Oxidative injury to hemoglobin is most commonly seen in glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency, which is inconsistent with the clinical scenario and also produces Coombs test-negative anemia.`],
