        q: `A 59-year-old man has experienced chronic fatigue and weight loss for the past 3 months. There are no remarkable findings on physical examination. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin, 10.0 g/dL (13.5–17.5. g/dL); hematocrit, 30.3%; MCV, 81 &#181;m<sup>3</sup> (80–100 &#181;m<sup>3</sup>); platelet count, 240,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); WBC count, 7,550/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); serum iron 20 &#181;g/dL (30–60 &#181;g/dL) ; total iron-binding capacity (transferrin level), 145 &#181;g/dL (240–450 &#181;g/dL); and serum ferritin, 565 ng/mL (12–150 ng/mL). Serum erythropoietin levels are low for the level of hemoglobin. Which of the following is the most likely mechanism of anemia?`,
