        optionFeedback: [` The patient is pancytopenic and has a macrocytic anemia, and the peripheral smear shows features of megaloblastic anemia (red cells are larger than normal and oval shaped; lack central pallor and appear full of hemoglobin; neutrophil is hypersegmented). Megaloblastic anemias are caused by defects in thymidine synthesis (a building block of DNA) that stem from deficiencies of vitamin B<sub>12</sub> or folate or from exposure to drugs that interfere with folate metabolism (e.g., methotrexate). Alcoholics typically have poor diets and are prone to develop folate deficiency, which is the likely culprit in this patient. `,`Extravascular hemolysis of antibody-coated cells would be associated with a normal to slightly elevated MCV and would not produce pancytopenia`,`Imbalance in synthesis of α-globin and β-globin chains defines thalassemia, which produces a microcytic anemia and doesn’t affect platelet or white cell production.`,`Increased susceptibility to lysis by complement is seen in paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria, a rare cause of intravascular hemolysis that is not in the differential diagnosis of a markedly macrocytic anemia.`,`Reduced deformability of RBC membranes, as may occur in hereditary spherocytosis, may lead to hemolysis, but cannot explain marked macrocytosis or pancytopenia. `],
