        q: `A 21-year-old woman with protein C deficiency develops recurrent pulmonary thromboembolism and is placed on anticoagulant therapy. Two weeks after initiation of this therapy, she has a sudden change in mental status and experiences difficulty speaking and swallowing. A cerebral angiogram shows a left middle cerebral artery occlusion. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin of 13 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL), platelet count of 65,400/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>), WBC count of 5,924/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>), prothrombin time (PT) of 12 seconds (11–15 seconds), and partial thromboplastin time (PTT) of 51 seconds (25–40 seconds). The anticoagulant therapy is discontinued. Which of the following anticoagulants is most likely to have caused these findings?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin)`, ` Heparin`,`Tissue plasminogen activator`,`Streptokinase`,`Warfarin`],
        optionFeedback: [`Acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin) therapy can produce bleeding but is not associated with thrombosis.`,`    Patients receiving heparin therapy to treat thrombosis, regardless of cause, (in this case, protein C deficiency), may develop antibodies that recognize platelet factor 4 in combination with heparin. These antibody-heparin-platelet factor 4 complexes activate platelets, leading to the formation of thrombi in both veins and arteries, often with serious and sometimes fatal consequences. The clotting is associated with the development of thrombocytopenia due to consumption of platelets, a condition called heparin-induced thrombocytopenia. The delay between the initiation of heparin and the appearance of thrombosis is consistent with the time needed for production of an acquired antibody in response to heparin therapy. Another clue to the diagnosis is the elevated PTT accompanied by a normal PT; heparin affects both coagulation tests, but the PTT is more sensitive to inhibition by heparin. `,`Tissue plasminogen activator activates the breakdown of fibrin and is associated with an increased risk of bleeding, not thrombosis.`,`Streptokinase activates the breakdown of fibrin and is associated with an increased risk of bleeding, not thrombosis.`,`Warfarin can paradoxically increase the risk of thrombosis in patients with protein C deficiency because protein C is a vitamin K-dependent factor. However, this risk is transient, occurs early after therapy is begun, usually takes the form of skin necrosis, and does not produce arterial thrombosis.`],
