        q: `A 23-year-old woman has a history of easy bruising. Physical examination shows multiple bruises ranging in color from red to blue to purple on her arms and legs. There is no organomegaly, and no deformities are noted. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin, 9.5 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL); hematocrit, 28.2% (36%–46%); platelet count, 229,300/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000-400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 7,185/mm<sup>3 </sup>(4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>),<sup> </sup>with normal differential count. Ristocetin-dependent platelet aggregation in patient plasma is reduced. Factor VIII activity is 30% (reference range 50%–150%). Which of the following is the most likely clinical consequence of this disease?`,
        q2: ``,
        q3: [],
        option: [`Bone marrow failure from aplasia`, `Excessive bleeding after oral surgery`,`Spontaneous bleeding in the knee joints`,`Recurrent bacterial infections`,`Recurrent deep venous thrombosis`],
        optionFeedback: [`Bone marrow failure from aplasia would be associated with pancytopenia.`,`   The clinical scenario and laboratory findings are consistent with von Willebrand disease, caused by either qualitative or quantitative defects in von Willebrand factor (vWF). Ristocetin is an antibiotic that causes platelets to stick to one another (known as agglutination, a test that is done in the clinical laboratory with formalin-fixed platelets) if there is an adequate amount of functional vWF.   VWF is required for normal platelet function and also acts as a carrier for factor VIII.    Hence factor VIII level is reduced in patients with von Willibrand disease. However, most patients with the common form of von Willebrand disease have sufficiently high levels of factor VIII such that secondary hemostasis (dependent on coagulation factor function) is normal; thus, the bleeding tendency stems only from inadequate platelet function. Functional defects in platelets are associated with petechial bleeding in skin and mucosa, abnormal menstrual bleeding, and increased bleeding following dental and surgical procedures. `,`Spontaneous bleeding in the knee joints is a feature of hemophilia, which is associated with severe factor VIII or factor IX deficiencies and is X-linked.`,`Recurrent bacterial infections are not a feature of von Willebrand disease, in which immune function is normal.`,`Recurrent deep venous thrombosis is not a feature of von Willebrand disease, in which patients are at risk of excessive bleeding, not clotting.`],
        optionStyleType: `st-upper-alpha`,
        answer: [1],
        ansText: `Rationale:- The clinical scenario and laboratory findings are consistent with von Willebrand disease, caused by either qualitative or quantitative defects in von Willebrand factor (vWF). Ristocetin is an antibiotic that causes platelets to stick to one another (known as agglutination, a test that is done in the clinical laboratory with formalin-fixed platelets) if there is an adequate amount of functional vWF.   VWF is required for normal platelet function and also acts as a carrier for factor VIII.    Hence factor VIII level is reduced in patients with von Willibrand disease. However, most patients with the common form of von Willebrand disease have sufficiently high levels of factor VIII such that secondary hemostasis (dependent on coagulation factor function) is normal; thus, the bleeding tendency stems only from inadequate platelet function. Functional defects in platelets are associated with petechial bleeding in skin and mucosa, abnormal menstrual bleeding, and increased bleeding following dental and surgical procedures.`,
