        option: [`Circulating toxin that injures capillary endothelium`, `Platelet activation and aggregation by large multimers of vWF`,`Defective ADP-induced platelet aggregation`,`Formation of autoantibodies to platelet glycoproteins IIb/IIIa and Ib-IX`,`Inappropriate release of thromboplastic substances into blood`],
        optionFeedback: [`A circulating toxin that injures capillary endothelium is associated with forms of hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS) that are caused by certain bacterial infections, such as with E.   coli strains that produce Shiga-like toxins. TTP and HUS are two different forms of thrombotic microangiopathy.`,`  The presence of antibodies against ADAMTS13 in the context of this clinical picture is diagnostic of thrombotic thrombocytopenia purpura (TTP). These autoantibodies inhibit ADAMTS13 function, leading to the appearance of very high molecular weight multimers of von Willebrand factor (VWF), which bind and activate platelets. This leads to platelet consumption and formation of platelet-rich thrombi in the kidney, brain, and other organs. Microvascular occlusion causes microangiopathic hemolytic anemia with fragmented red cells. `,`Defective ADP-induced platelet aggregation would be associated with evidence of platelet dysfunction (e.g., mucosal and cutaneous petechial bleeding) but other features of this case (renal failure, antibodies against ADAMTS13) would be absent.`,`Formation of autoantibodies to platelet glycoproteins IIb/IIIa and Ib-IX is associated with immune thrombocytopenia purpura, which usually presents with evidence of mucosal and cutaneous petechial bleeding. Schistocytes are absent.`,`Inappropriate release of thromboplastic substances into blood is associated with DIC, which is not associated with auto-antibodies against ADAMTS13.`],
