        q: `A 26-year-old man has a 10-week history of fever with nonproductive cough. On examination, his temperature is 37.4&#176; C. A chest radiograph shows a 4-cm left upper lobe nodule. CBC shows hemoglobin, 13.3 g/dL (13.5–17.5. g/dL); hematocrit, 40.5% (41%–53%); platelet count, 281,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 13,760/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>) with 38% segmented neutrophils, 2% bands, 45% lymphocytes, and 15% monocytes. What is the most likely diagnosis?`,
