        q: `A 36-year-old woman has a 1-week history of cough and fever. On physical examination, her temperature is 38.3&#176; C.  She has diffuse crackles in all lung fields. A chest radiograph shows extensive bilateral infiltrates. CBC shows hemoglobin, 13.9 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL); hematocrit, 42% (36%–46%); MCV, 89 &#181;m<sup>3</sup> (80–100 &#181;m<sup>3</sup>); platelet count, 350,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 56,000/mm<sup>3</sup>(4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>), with 63% segmented neutrophils, 16% bands, 7% metamyelocytes, 3% myelocytes, 1% blasts, 8% lymphocytes, and 2% monocytes. A bone marrow biopsy is obtained and shows increased numbers of myeloid cells that show left-shifted, but normal, maturation. Karyotype performed on the bone marrow aspirate shows a normal female karyotype (46,XX). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?`,
