        q: `A 23-year-old, previously healthy man has experienced malaise, low-grade fever, and sore throat for 2 weeks. On physical examination, his temperature is 37.6&#176; C, and he has pharyngeal erythema without exudation. There is tender cervical, axillary, and inguinal lymphadenopathy. Laboratory studies show hemoglobin, 12.2 g/dL (13.5–17.5. g/dL); hematocrit, 36.6% (41%–53%); platelet count, 190,200/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 8,940/mm<sup>3</sup>(4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). His peripheral blood smear is shown in the figure. Based on these findings and a laboratory test result, his doctor advises against any antibiotic treatment and he recovers after 6 weeks. What is the most important mechanism of recovery in this case? <img src="../images/f009-q035-9780323640251.png" alt="icon"/>`,
        q2: ``,
