        option: [`Activation of cytotoxic T cell response`, `Activation of the complement cascade`,`Activation of macrophages`,`Production of neutralizing antibodies`,` Activation of B cells`],
        optionFeedback: [` The chief differential diagnosis in this case is bacterial pharyngitis versus a viral infection, particularly infectious mononucleosis. The figure shows atypical lymphocytes with abundant cytoplasm that are sticking to adjacent red cells, so-called kissing cells. These lymphocytes are cytotoxic T cells; the binding to red cells is presumably mediated by adhesion molecules and is characteristic of certain viral infections, particularly those mediated by herpesviruses. The clinical scenario given above is entirely consistent with infectious mononucleosis caused by Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) infection, which would need to be confirmed with a mono-spot test (the laboratory test referred to in the case). `,`Activation of the innate immune system (e.g., complement cascade) has little role in effective responses to EBV infection.`,`Activation of the innate immune system (e.g., macrophages) has little role in effective responses to EBV infection.`,`Patients develop antibodies against EBV antigens, but these do not protect patients from reactivation of the infection if T-cell immunity wanes.`,`B cells are the target of EBV infection and are activated to proliferate by the virus. It is the elimination of these cells by cytotoxic T cells that produces the symptoms in those with infectious mononucleosis.`],
