        q: `A 70-year-old man has a 6-month history of increasing fatigue. On physical examination, he has nontender axillary and cervical lymphadenopathy, but there is no hepatosplenomegaly. The CBC shows hemoglobin, 9.5 g/dL (13.5–17.5. g/dL); hematocrit, 28% (41%–53%); MCV, 90 &#181;m<sup>3</sup> (80–100 &#181;m<sup>3</sup>); platelet count, 120,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count, 42,000/mm<sup>3</sup> (4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). His peripheral blood smear shows a monotonous population of small, round, mature-looking lymphocytes. Flow cytometry reveals these cells to be CD19+, CD5+, and terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase negative (TdT&#8722;). Molecular analysis of the abnormal cells in his blood is most likely to reveal which of the following alterations?`,
