        optionFeedback: [` The clinical, morphologic, and immunophenotypic features are all consistent with chronic lymphocytic leukemia, a tumor of mature CD5+, CD19 + B cells. CD5 is expressed on T cells and a small subset of normal B cells. The cells in this tumor uniformly have clonal rearrangement of immunoglobulin genes and express immunoglobulin on their surface. `,`Clonal rearrangement of T-cell receptor genes is a feature of T cell neoplasms; CD19, which is positive on the tumor cells, is a B-cell specific marker.`,`t(8;14) leading to MYC overexpression is a feature of Burkitt lymphoma, a very aggressive neoplasm in which the tumor cells do not express CD5. The tumor cells may involve the peripheral blood but have a “blastoid” appearance.`,`t(9;22) leading to BCR-ABL rearrangement is a typical feature of chronic myeloid leukemia and certain B acute lymphoblastic leukemias (B-ALL), which pursue an aggressive course and are associated with circulating blasts. B-ALL usually expresses CD19 but is CD5 negative.`,`t(14;18) leading to BCL2 overexpression is a feature of follicular lymphoma, which pursues an indolent course and is a CD19-positive B cell tumor; however, follicular lymphoma cells do not express CD5 and have an irregular, “cleaved” appearance when they appear in the peripheral blood.`],
