        q: `A 60-year-old woman presents for a routine check-up. On physical examination, she had palpable nontender axillary and inguinal lymph nodes, and the spleen tip was palpable. Laboratory studies showed hemoglobin, 13.1 g/dL (12.0–16.0 g/dL); hematocrit, 38.5% (36–46%); MCV, 90 &#181;m<sup>3 </sup>(80–100 &#181;m<sup>3</sup>); platelet count, 189,000/mm<sup>3 </sup>(150,000–400,000/mm<sup>3</sup>); and WBC count 31,300/mm<sup>3 </sup>(4,500–11,000/mm<sup>3</sup>). The peripheral blood smear is shown in the figure. Which of the following clinical features is typical of this disease? <img src="../images/f009-q041-9780323640251.png" alt="icon"/>`,
