        optionFeedback: [`Cytomegalovirus is not oncogenic.`,` Patients with HIV infection are at higher risk of B-cell lymphomas, mostly diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and Burkitt lymphoma. Many of these tumors are EBV-positive, particularly in the setting of HIV-related T-cell immunosuppression. Such tumors have a predilection for extra nodal sites, including the gut wall and the central nervous system. `,`HIV infection increases the risk of lymphoma by suppressing immunity against oncogenic viruses such as EBV but is not itself oncogenic.`,`Human herpesvirus 8 is associated with rare aggressive B-cell lymphomas that present as effusions. It is also associated with Kaposi sarcoma, which is not a lymphoid malignancy. `,`Human T-cell lymphotropic virus type 1 is associated with adult T-cell lymphoma/leukemia, a T cell neoplasm that is not increased in patients with HIV infection.`],
