        option: [`Acute lymphoblastic lymphoma`, `Burkitt lymphoma`,`Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma`,` Hodgkin lymphoma`,`Small lymphocytic lymphoma`],
        optionFeedback: [`Acute lymphoblastic lymphoma is a T-cell lymphoma that typically occurs in children and involves the mediastinum. It is TdT positive and not associated with BCL6 mutations.`,`Burkitt lymphoma is associated with MYC translocations, not mutations in BCL6.`,` The clinical, immunophenotypic, and genetic features best fit diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, an aggressive tumor of large B cells that is the most common lymphoma in adults and responds well to chemotherapy. Mutations that lead to overexpression of the BCL6 gene are common in this type of lymphoma. It may involve nodal or extra nodal sites and is a form of non-Hodgkin lymphoma; one characteristic that separates non-Hodgkin lymphoma from Hodgkin lymphoma is that Hodgkin lymphoma rarely involves Waldeyer ring, the lymphoid tissues that are present in the oropharynx.  `,`Hodgkin lymphoma is a B-cell tumor in which rare tumor giant cells are seen in a predominant background of reactive inflammatory cells. It rarely involves Waldeyer ring.`,`Small lymphocytic lymphoma is a tumor that is identical to chronic lymphocytic leukemia, but with fewer circulating cells. It is an indolent tumor of small B cells that are CD10 negative and CD5 positive. It involves multiple lymph nodes as well as the liver and spleen.`],
