        optionFeedback: [`Bence Jones proteinuria is defined by the presence of free light chains in the urine. This is most commonly seen in patients with multiple myeloma, which is more likely to present with CRAB criteria (hypercal<u>c</u>emia, <u>r</u>enal failure, <u>a</u>nemia, <u>b</u>one disease) than hyperviscosity.`,`Hypercalcemia is a feature of multiple myeloma, not lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma. Myeloma cells increase osteoclastic activity by up regulation of RANKL (receptor activator of nuclear factor kappa-Β ligand) production. `,`Karyotype with t(14;18) translocation is a feature of follicular lymphoma, which is not associated with symptoms related to a hyperviscosity of blood.`,` The clinical and morphologic findings are consistent with lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma, a tumor of B cells that secretes IgM in sufficient quantities to give rise to a monoclonal IgM spike in the bone marrow. Large amounts of IgM in the serum cause symptoms related to blood hyperviscosity, such as visual disturbances, dizziness, headache, and Raynaud phenomenon. The combination of monoclonal IgM spike in the serum and complications of hyperviscosity is sometimes referred to by its older name, Waldenstrom macroglobulinemia. `,`WBC count of 255,000/mm<sup>3</sup> would be highly unlikely in lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma, which usually has a low burden of circulating cells. `],
