        optionFeedback: [`Mucosa-associated lymphoid tumors are typically associated with H. pylori infection (which may have been the reason for her taking omeprazole), but are not associated with polycythemia.`,`Monoclonal gammopathy is not associated with progression of polycythemia vera. It is associated with multiple myeloma, plasmacytoma, certain B-cell neoplasms, and MGUS (monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance), a precursor lesion for multiple myeloma.`,`    The patient's presentation and markedly elevated hemoglobin and hematocrit are characteristic of polycythemia vera (PV), a myeloproliferative neoplasm associated with activating mutations in the JAK2 gene. Activated JAK2 lies downstream of multiple growth factor receptors, and as a result, patients with PV often have elevated levels of red cells, platelets, and granulocytes. Symptoms are most often related to the increase in red cells (polycythemia) and its associated plethora and hyperviscosity, leading to headaches, dizziness, splenic congestion, and an increased risk of thrombosis. PV frequently progresses to a “spent-phase” characterized by bone marrow fibrosis, which in turn results in extramedullary hematopoiesis and splenomegaly.  `,`Myeloproliferative neoplasms rarely, if ever, undergo spontaneous remission; the typical natural history is progression either to myelofibrosis or acute leukemia.`,`Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) can transform to acute B-lymphoblastic leukemia; however, this is not observed with polycythemia vera or any of the other myeloproliferative neoplasms. `],
