        optionFeedback: [` Primary myelofibrosis is a myeloproliferative neoplasm in which the marrow becomes fibrotic due to secretion of fibrogenic cytokines such as transforming growth factor (TGF)-beta by neoplastic megakaryocytes. Initially, the marrow is hypercellular, with tri-lineage proliferation. As this disease advances and the marrow becomes fibrotic and hematopoiesis shifts to the spleen, which may enlarge dramatically. Typically, there are immature myeloid as well as erythroid cells in the peripheral blood, both because they are released abnormally from the distorted marrow due to the fibrosis, and also because they tend to escape from sites of extramedullary hematopoiesis, particularly the spleen.  `,`Granulomas with Histoplasma capsulatum can cause splenomegaly, but usually not marked splenomegaly. It is not associated with clusters of abnormal megakaryocytes.`,`Hodgkin lymphoma usually presents with splenomegaly only late in the course of the disease. It is not associated with clusters of abnormal megakaryocytes.`,`Metastatic adenocarcinoma is an unlikely cause of splenomegaly. It is not associated with clusters of abnormal megakaryocytes.`,`Portal hypertension can cause splenomegaly, but we have no evidence of liver disease, and extramedullary hematopoiesis is a much more likely explanation for the splenomegaly. It is not associated with marrow fibrosis or clusters of abnormal megakaryocytes.`],
